context: The Fitzroy Tavern is a pub situated at <a0_0>16 Charlotte Street<a0_0/> in the <a1_0>Fitzrovia<a1_0/> district, to which it gives its name. It became famous (or according to others, infamous) during a period spanning the 1920s to the mid-1950s as a meeting place for many of London's artists, intellectuals and bohemians such as Dylan Thomas, Augustus John, and George Orwell. Several establishments in <a2_0>Soho<a2_0/>, London, have associations with well-known, post-war literary and artistic figures, including the Pillars of Hercules, The Colony Room and the Coach and Horses. <a3_0>The <a4_0>Canonbury<a4_0/> Tavern<a3_0/>, Canonbury, was the prototype for Orwell's ideal English pub, The Moon Under Water.
